                    <h2 id="introduction" style="margin-top: 0;">Introduction</h2>
                    <p>Software has been centred around screens for decades. We moved from desktop computing to mobile applications, from websites to native apps, and from command-line systems to graphical user interfaces. Every advancement enhanced accessibility and decreased friction.</p>
                    <p>We are now getting close to yet another turning point: <strong>Conversation-driven execution is replacing interface-driven software.</strong></p>
                    <p>A new operating system or app store might not be at the core of this shift. It may be WhatsApp, powered by AI agents.</p>

                    <h2 id="distribution">Distribution Has Already Been Resolved</h2>
                    <p>WhatsApp is one of the most extensively used digital platforms in history, with over two billion monthly active users worldwide, according to Meta.</p>
                    <p>WhatsApp is more than just a chat service in marketplaces in sections of Europe, South Asia, Africa, and Latin America. It serves as a digital infrastructure. It is used by businesses to run shopfronts. It is used by customer service. It is where payments are started.</p>
                    <p>In contrast, there is increasing conflict in the conventional mobile app ecosystem:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>After just one use, a sizable portion of consumers give up on apps.</li>
                        <li>Few, if any, new apps are downloaded by the typical smartphone user each month.</li>
                        <li>New applications are becoming more difficult to distribute.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>It has already been surmounted by messaging platforms.</p>

                    <h2 id="intent-expression">From Interface Navigation to Intent Expression</h2>
                    <p>Traditional applications use structured navigation:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Menus</li>
                        <li>Dashboards</li>
                        <li>Forms</li>
                        <li>Workflows with multiple steps</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Before obtaining value from software, users must understand how it operates. This model is reversed by AI agents. Users express intent rather than navigating features:</p>
                    <blockquote>
                        "Next Friday, book a flight to Berlin."<br>
                        "This document should be summarised."<br>
                        "At six in the morning, arrange a ride to the airport."
                    </blockquote>
                    <p>Interpreting, reasoning, executing, and responding are all done by the system. This signifies a fundamental change from manipulating interfaces to orchestrating outcomes.</p>

                    <h2 id="proof">Proof That the Transition Is Taking Place</h2>
                    <h3>Klarna's Use of AI</h3>
                    <p>Klarna revealed in 2024 that its AI assistant was managing a significant percentage of customer service conversations, completing tasks comparable to those of hundreds of support agents while preserving customer satisfaction levels.</p>
                    <p>The lesson is simple: <strong>Resolution is more important to users than interface.</strong></p>

                    <h3>WeChat as an Example</h3>
                    <p>Tencent converted WeChat into a multipurpose platform that combines public services, healthcare reservations, payments, and transportation into a single messaging interface. WeChat serves as an example of how messaging can develop into a daily operational layer.</p>
                    <p>Similar developments on WhatsApp, bolstered by sophisticated AI agents, might take place on a worldwide scale.</p>

