                    <h2 id="infrastructure">When Applications Become Infrastructure</h2>
                    <p>An essential skill is demonstrated by open-source agent frameworks like OpenClaw: autonomous systems capable of navigating digital surroundings, interacting with interfaces, and carrying out tasks on behalf of users.</p>
                    <p>Think about transportation. Instead of opening the Uber app, entering pickup details, selecting ride options, and confirming payment, a user could simply message:</p>
                    <blockquote>"Tomorrow at six in the morning, I need a ride to the airport."</blockquote>
                    <p>An intelligent agent could:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Check your calendar commitments.</li>
                        <li>Verify the flight schedule.</li>
                        <li>Select ride preferences.</li>
                        <li>Execute the booking.</li>
                        <li>Deliver confirmation.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Uber does not vanish under this model. It becomes infrastructure accessed through conversational orchestration. Applications compete on service performance and API dependability rather than interface design.</p>

                    <h2 id="economics">The Economics of Interface Elimination</h2>
                    <p>Friction is introduced with each extra screen. The chance of abandoning rises with each further step.</p>
                    <p>Multi-step processes are condensed into a single transaction by conversational agents. Rather than: <em>Open → Navigate → Search → Filter → Confirm → Pay</em>, we move towards:</p>
                    <blockquote>"Find the most affordable flight arriving before 5 p.m."</blockquote>
                    <p>Navigation is replaced by intent. This increases digital accessibility for a wider range of demographics and lessens cognitive burden.</p>

                    <h2 id="implications">Strategic Implications for Builders</h2>
                    <p>Most software products today are still designed around dashboards.</p>
                    <p>Dashboards assume:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Time commitment</li>
                        <li>Technical expertise</li>
                        <li>Frequent interaction</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Conversational AI makes the following assumptions:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Natural language</li>
                        <li>Focus on outcomes</li>
                        <li>Very little onboarding</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>It's possible that the upcoming generation of high-leverage software will be completely different from conventional applications. It may appear as a contact saved in a messaging app.</p>

                    <h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion: The Third Wave</h2>
                    <p>Computing history can be viewed in three phases:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Command-line interfaces</li>
                        <li>Graphical user interfaces</li>
                        <li>Conversational agent interfaces</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>WhatsApp combined with AI agents may represent the global adoption layer of this third phase. Not because artificial intelligence is new. But because distribution and intelligence are finally converging at scale.</p>
                    <p>When that convergence occurs, interfaces do not simply improve. They become invisible.</p>

